found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} f6 {This is an exciting
continuation. Black attacks the White bishop with tempo and takes control of
the e5-square, but also weakens the light squares around his king. The
emerging positions are adventurous, active, and original with chances for both
sides.} 3. Bd2 {Here White can also play 3.Bh4 or 3.Bf4. All of these moves
are fine, but I like Bd2 the most for a couple of reasons. We already
discussed the most important one, the number of lines to learn will be reduced.
All variations will be connected with a Black strike in the center with e7-e5.
There is no other plan to go for after 2... f6. The next reason is that the
position will be easy to play with the White pieces. And finally, the
positions will be fresh, active, and adventurous. There are quite a few tricks
for Black to navigate, while White is never worse.} c5 {This is the most
aggressive Black option here, but because of the inserted moves ...f6 and Bd2
there is no way that Black can transpose to the positions where ...Nf6 is
possible. Because of that, White's position is favorable. Now White picks up
the pawn on the c5.} 4. dxc5 {It's important to capture on c5 to make use of
our advantage in development. The idea is to put a pawn on e4 next and open
the position.} e5 {This is the most aggressive and Black's best option here.}
5. e4 {The best move here. White has a lead in the development and the ...f6
move has created development problems for Black, so White has to start opening
the position in the center to expose Black's weaknesses.} d4 {This is not a
good move because it cedes all the light squares on the diagonal a2-g8 to
White.} 6. Bc4 {A nice move that immediately shows how the light squares in
the Black camp are exposed.} Bxc5 7. b4 {White grabs space on the queenside
with tempo.} Bd6 8. c3 {The d4-pawn is under attack before Black manages to
develop his pieces to support this pawn.} dxc3 {This offers White complete
domination in the center and once White has played Qb3, Black's position could
quickly collapse.} 9. Nxc3 Bxb4 {Black gets the pawn now.} 10. Qb3 {White
sacrifice the pawn. In return, the bishop pair is worth at least two pawns in
this position.} Bxc3 {The b4-bishop and g8-knight are under attack, so Black
is forced to take on c3.} 11. Bxc3 Ne7 12. f4 {With a huge advantage for White.
Black is undeveloped and the Bc3 and Bc4 are monsters. It's hard to suggest
any move for Black.} *

