move has created development problems for Black, so White has to start opening
the position in the center to expose Black's weaknesses.} Bxc5 {Black regains
the pawn.} 6. Nc3 Ne7 {Black defends the d5-pawn.} 7. Qh5+ {A great move, with
which White disturbs Black's plans of castling and creates new pawn weaknesses
on the kingside. Also, this move vacates the d1-square and allows White to
castle queenside next.} g6 8. Qf3 {And we have on the board almost the exact
same position as in the variation with ...e6, which is discussed in the main
course. The only difference is that Black's pawn is on e5 which means he has a
more stable center.} Nbc6 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Bh6 {White has a small but stable
advantage here. Black's king is much more vulnerable than White's and could
become a target.} *

