found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} f6 {This is an exciting
continuation. Black attacks the White bishop with tempo and takes control of
the e5-square, but also weakens the light squares around his king. The
emerging positions are adventurous, active, and original with chances for both
sides.} 3. Bd2 {Here White can also play 3.Bh4 or 3.Bf4. All of these moves
are fine, but I like Bd2 the most for a couple of reasons. We already
discussed the most important one, the number of lines to learn will be reduced.
All variations will be connected with a Black strike in the center with e7-e5.
There is no other plan to go for after 2... f6. The next reason is that the
position will be easy to play with the White pieces. And finally, the
positions will be fresh, active, and adventurous. There are quite a few tricks
for Black to navigate, while White is never worse.} e5 {This is a very
straightforward move. Black immediately wants to take advantage of the move f6
and plays for activity. The obvious drawback is that by move three, he has not
developed any of his pieces yet. This could cause him some problems, as we
will see.} 4. dxe5 {White opens the game in the center and counter-strikes
before Black manages to develop his pieces.} fxe5 5. e4 {White keeps bombing
the center. Black has to be careful now because of his lack of development.
The position is opened, and both pawns on the e5 and d5 could be exposed,
together with the Black king on e8. It is easy to go wrong here with Black
immediately. Let us see why.} Nf6 {Black has to start developing his pieces.
This is the best move, as this knight protects the king on e8 because Qh5+ is
not possible anymore. 3... Nc6 will almost always transpose to this line.} 6.
exd5 {Now the fun starts. White can reach a nice position in a very easy way.
The first step is to take on d5, destroy the Black centre and weaken the
e5-pawn. After that, White starts developing his pieces and puts pressure on
the weak e-pawn.} c6 {This gambit variation is very interesting. Black
sacrifices a pawn for quick development instead of losing tempi with 6...Qxd5.}
7. dxc6 {White should accept the sacrifice. The best way to play against
gambits is to take what is on offer.} Nxc6 {Black recaptures on c6 with a
developing move.} 8. Nc3 {It is better to develop the b1 knight first as this
move allows White to try and exchange the dark-squared bishops later.} Bc5 {
Black has sacrificed a pawn for quick development and now his pieces are on
great squares.} 9. Be3 {White has to be cautious here. He is a pawn up, but
Black's pieces are very well placed. It is important to understand that the
best play in similar situations is to exchange some of the pieces, especially
the queens, because without the queens Black's lead in development would not
be such a big deal.} Qe7 {Black can take on d1, but he can also avoid the
queen trade. 9...Qb6 or 9...Qa5 would not be any different here.} 10. Bxc5 {
White takes the bishop.} Qxc5 {Only move. This is why the position would be
the same after 9... Qb6 and 9... Qa5.} 11. Nf3 {White is a pawn up and if he
manages to finish his development undisturbed, he would be better.} Bg4 {Black
finds the best square for his light-squared bishop.} 12. Qd3 {White must not
allow an e5-e4 break.} e4 {Black gives up yet another pawn in order to open
the e-file and confuse the White pieces.} 13. Nxe4 {White has to take the pawn.
} Qe7 {This move puts some pressure on the e-file, but after his next move
White will manage to take control of the game.} 14. O-O-O {White temporarily
leaves the knight undefended, but he will immediately win the piece back if
Black takes it.} Nxe4 {Black takes the piece.} 15. Re1 {White has to play
precisely to get the piece back.} Bf5 {Black protects the knight once again.}
16. Nd2 {And White brings another piece to the attack.} O-O {Black does not
have any more pieces to keep the pressure and has to withdraw.} 17. Nxe4 {
White takes the piece back and is two pawns up. White is almost winning here.}
*

