e5 immediately @@StartBracket@@which we saw earlier@@EndBracket@@, Black can
prepare the e7-e5 break with this knight move.} 4. c4 {And now the fun starts.
I only managed to find two games in the database that reached this position.
This is a unique variation with incredible chances to be creative and to
out-prepare your opponent.} dxc4 {Black temporarily takes the c4-pawn and puts
direct pressure on the d4-pawn.} 5. e3 {After ...dxc4 the d4-pawn is under
attack, so White has to protect it.} e5 {This move is not that good after the
exchange on c4.} 6. Bxc4 {White just retakes the pawn and brings his bishop to
a great square.} exd4 {This aggressive move is in the spirit of the position,
but because of the weak position of the Black king White will get a huge
initiative.} 7. Qb3 {This move points out how weak the Black kingside is. The
g8-knight is under attack and it does not have a good square to go to.} Nh6 {
This is the only move that saves the knight and protects the f7-square.} 8. Nf3
{White keeps activating his pieces.} dxe3 {This is the direct approach. Black
does not want to wait and forces the pawn exchange in the centre.} 9. Bxe3 {
The position opens for the dark-squared bishop.} Na5 {A direct move with which
Black intends to neutralize the pressure on the a2-g8 diagonal.} 10. Qa4+ {
White saves his queen with tempo.} c6 11. Be2 {And now the bishop retreats.}
Nf5 {This move temporarily drives back the bishop, but the a5 knight is still
dominated by the White pieces.} 12. Bd2 {White is much better with b2-b4 in
the air.} *

