1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Pseudo -
Trompowsky'! This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an
overview of the Pseudo - Trompowsky. With the Pseudo - Trompowsky, you will,
for sure, surprise your opponent and get him out of his preparation. It's
aggressive but simple to play and easy to learn. With this opening, you will
be creative right from the start. I did not analyze the absolute mainlines of
1. d4 that have been played oh so many times before, but the lines that I
found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c5 {This is one of the three
main lines. Black could also continue with 2...h6 , but that would only
transpose to one of these three lines following 3.Bh4. The move ...c5 is
Black's most active option. The d4-pawn is challenged, and the queen is ready
to move to b6, increasing the pressure on the d4- and b2-squares.} 3. e3 {
White has to defend the d4-pawn. In this position, 3. e3 is much better than 3.
c3 , because it keeps open the option of playing Nc3 in case Black plays Qb6
with a double-edged imbalanced position.} Bf5 {Black tries to mix the move
order by playing the light-squared bishop to f5 first. He delays revealing his
main plan and could proceed with ...Nf6 and/or ...Nc6, but he could also play
the annoying ...Qb6. White has to be careful here, and reply accurately to
what Black is doing.} 4. Nc3 {White could play 4.Nf3 , which would lead to
complicated play with chances for both sides. In the spirit of our repertoire,
I will present you with a line that is closer to equal but is easy to play
with a nice position and a simple plan. We will go for Nc3 here to exert
pressure on the d5-pawn immediately and not allow Black too much activity.} Nc6
{Black develops his queen's knight first.} 5. dxc5 f6 6. e4 dxe4 {Black can
take on e4 with either the pawn or the bishop. After dxe4 the pawn looks very
good in the center but the light-squared bishop loses some of its scope behind
the pawn.} 7. Be3 {White moves the dark-squared bishop back to e3 where it
keeps an eye on the c5-pawn.} e5 {Black tries to get some space and control in
the center.} 8. Bc4 {But now after ...e5 the White squares have become weak,
so White occupies the fantastic a2-g8 diagonal with his bishop.} Qxd1+ {Black
is a little bit worse and tries to reach equality by exchanging the heavy
artillery.} 9. Rxd1 Rd8 10. Rxd8+ Nxd8 11. b4 {Black managed to exchange a few
pieces, but the remaining White pieces are more active and the queenside pawns
look very dangerous.} Ne7 {This knight goes is heading to c6, after which the
dark-squared bishop can finally come into play on e7.} 12. Nge2 {White also
develops his last minor piece and is ready for action on the queenside.} Nec6
13. Nd5 {The position is really bad for Black. The central pawns look good,
but they are firmly blocked. Black also struggles to find squares for his
pieces. White's pawns on the queenside are very scary and all his pieces are
just much better. White has a big advantage.} *

