non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c5 {This is one of the three
main lines. Black could also continue with 2...h6 , but that would only
transpose to one of these three lines following 3.Bh4. The move ...c5 is
Black's most active option. The d4-pawn is challenged, and the queen is ready
to move to b6, increasing the pressure on the d4- and b2-squares.} 3. e3 {
White has to defend the d4-pawn. In this position, 3. e3 is much better than 3.
c3 , because it keeps open the option of playing Nc3 in case Black plays Qb6
with a double-edged imbalanced position.} h6 {Let us have a look at the 3...
h6 lines. It is worth mentioning here, that after e3, if Black plays h6, then
the bishop goes back to h4, and if he plays f6, then to f4.} 4. Bh4 Qb6 {As we
mentioned before, this queen move introduces Black's most active plan.} 5. Nc3
e6 {The pawn on d5 was hanging, so Black defends it. 5...Qxb2 is not good
because of 6.Nxd5.} 6. Nf3 {This is a nice developing move that defends d4 and
prepares short castling.} Qxb2 {White has to be prepared for this move in this
variation.} 7. Nb5 {This move is mandatory after Qxb2, threatening Nc7. Black
has won a pawn, but White's lead in development and initiative is huge. He has
developed three minor pieces whilst Black did not develop a single one. Also,
the Black queen is on b2 and he will lose more time to get it back. The
arising positions will be double-edged, but in my opinion, the initiative is
more than enough for the sacrificed material. It is much easier to play this
position with White.} Qb4+ 8. c3 Qa5 9. Bg3 {The idea is very clear: Nc7 is
back on the table. The only way to defend against it is ...Na6, but then the
White knight on b5 will be a great piece and Black will not be able to chase
it away easily.} Na6 {The only move that prevents Nc7+.} 10. Nd2 {White
transfers the knight over to the queenside to put even more pressure on the
Black position and attack the queen.} c4 {This seems to be very promising for
Black and here White has to be vigilant. Black is behind in development and
the best chance for him is to keep the position closed to get some time for
mobilizing his pieces. If he manages to do that, White would be a clear pawn
down for nothing, so he has to play aggressively and sacrifice a piece for the
initiative.} 11. Rb1 {The knight on b5 was hanging, so White has to protect it.
} Nf6 {After closing the center, Black has to start developing his pieces.} 12.
e4 {Because the b5-knight is not under attack, White can try to open the game
in the center with e4 first.} Bd7 {The second option is to attack the
b5-knight and force White into action.} 13. Bxc4 {This piece sacrifice is
crucial. White has to open the game immediately and capitalize on his better
development and more active pieces before Black manages to catch up. If Black
consolidates with the pawn up, White will be in trouble. After this move White
gets tremendous compensation and initiative for the sacrificed piece. With
accurate play, White will get the advantage.} dxc4 {Black has to take the
piece.} 14. Nxc4 {And now the knight joins the attack on the Black queen.} Qd8
15. Ncd6+ {A fantastic position. Black has an extra bishop, but it looks like
it is White who is a piece up. The White pieces are dangerously close to the
Black king, and the knight on a6 is a mere observer.} Bxd6 {Black has to take
to reduce the number of White pieces in the attack and vacate the f8 square
for the king.} 16. Nxd6+ Kf8 17. Nxb7 {White now has two pawns for the piece,
the Black queen is under attack and the other pieces are completely
disconnected. White has a big positional advantage.} Qc8 {This is the only
square for the queen. All other possible queen moves are bad.} 18. O-O {Again
a great picture. Black has a knight for two pawns but it looks like it is
White who has the extra piece. The Black pieces are badly placed or still
undeveloped, whilst the White pieces are great and the central pawns are ready
to start marching forward. If Black allows it, White will play e5 and c4 and
get enormous space and control over the position. Despite being a piece down,
I prefer White, as Black is without any active play here.} *

