1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Pseudo -
Trompowsky'! This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an
overview of the Pseudo - Trompowsky. With the Pseudo - Trompowsky, you will,
for sure, surprise your opponent and get him out of his preparation. It's
aggressive but simple to play and easy to learn. With this opening, you will
be creative right from the start. I did not analyze the absolute mainlines of
1. d4 that have been played oh so many times before, but the lines that I
found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c5 {This is one of the three
main lines. Black could also continue with 2...h6 , but that would only
transpose to one of these three lines following 3.Bh4. The move ...c5 is
Black's most active option. The d4-pawn is challenged, and the queen is ready
to move to b6, increasing the pressure on the d4- and b2-squares.} 3. e3 {
White has to defend the d4-pawn. In this position, 3. e3 is much better than 3.
c3 , because it keeps open the option of playing Nc3 in case Black plays Qb6
with a double-edged imbalanced position.} h6 {Let us have a look at the 3...
h6 lines. It is worth mentioning here, that after e3, if Black plays h6, then
the bishop goes back to h4, and if he plays f6, then to f4.} 4. Bh4 Qb6 {As we
mentioned before, this queen move introduces Black's most active plan.} 5. Nc3
e6 {The pawn on d5 was hanging, so Black defends it. 5...Qxb2 is not good
because of 6.Nxd5.} 6. Nf3 {This is a nice developing move that defends d4 and
prepares short castling.} Qxb2 {White has to be prepared for this move in this
variation.} 7. Nb5 {This move is mandatory after Qxb2, threatening Nc7. Black
has won a pawn, but White's lead in development and initiative is huge. He has
developed three minor pieces whilst Black did not develop a single one. Also,
the Black queen is on b2 and he will lose more time to get it back. The
arising positions will be double-edged, but in my opinion, the initiative is
more than enough for the sacrificed material. It is much easier to play this
position with White.} Qb4+ 8. c3 Qa5 9. Bg3 {The idea is very clear: Nc7 is
back on the table. The only way to defend against it is ...Na6, but then the
White knight on b5 will be a great piece and Black will not be able to chase
it away easily.} Na6 {The only move that prevents Nc7+.} 10. Nd2 {White
transfers the knight over to the queenside to put even more pressure on the
Black position and attack the queen.} cxd4 {This is an attempt to reduce the
tension in the center. The idea is to simplify the position and reduce the
pressure by exchanging a few pawns and pieces.} 11. exd4 {It is better to take
with the e-pawn here to keep the b4-square under control.} Nf6 {Black wants to
develop his kingside and castle.} 12. Rb1 {White defends the b5-knight and
puts pressure on the b7-pawn.} Bd7 {Black starts attacking the knight.} 13. Be2
{The threat of Nd6+ is not running away, and White has to be mindful of his
development to maintain the initiative.} Be7 {Now Black is only one move away
from castling so White has to be direct.} 14. Nd6+ {White does not need to
hurry with this move, but as soon as Black is ready to castle, he should play
it.} Bxd6 {Black has to take the knight.} 15. Bxd6 {The bishop turns into a
monster on d6. Black cannot castle and with the king in the center, it will be
hard for him to maintain the balance.} Qxc3 {Grabbing this pawn is possible,
but Black's position will collapse in the next couple of moves. With the king
still in the center, it is unwise to start counting material. All the White
pieces will join the attack on the Black king.} 16. O-O {White calmly castles
and allows Black to run with the material. The White king was also fairly
vulnerable in the middle but now the hunt for the Black king can start.} Rc8 {
Instead of taking yet another pawn, Black would like to play ...Rc6 and expel
the White dark-squared bishop from the a3-f8 diagonal so that Black can castle.
Also, he prevents Rc1. However, Rc1 is not the main idea here. The b7-pawn
will fall now.} 17. Be5 {White first improves the position of the bishop and
his next move will be Rxb7, which was not immediately possible because of Qc6.}
O-O {Black immediately castles.} 18. Rxb7 {I studied this position for quite a
while and the more I looked, the better it felt for White. The b7-rook is a
beast and everything on the 7th rank is in danger now. Black is still a pawn
up but White has several threats. Bxf6 followed by Rxd7 is possible, Rxa7 is
possible and the a6-knight is also hanging. White has a huge initiative and a
clear advantage here.} *

