1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Pseudo -
Trompowsky'! This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an
overview of the Pseudo - Trompowsky. With the Pseudo - Trompowsky, you will,
for sure, surprise your opponent and get him out of his preparation. It's
aggressive but simple to play and easy to learn. With this opening, you will
be creative right from the start. I did not analyze the absolute mainlines of
1. d4 that have been played oh so many times before, but the lines that I
found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c5 {This is one of the three
main lines. Black could also continue with 2...h6 , but that would only
transpose to one of these three lines following 3.Bh4. The move ...c5 is
Black's most active option. The d4-pawn is challenged, and the queen is ready
to move to b6, increasing the pressure on the d4- and b2-squares.} 3. e3 {
White has to defend the d4-pawn. In this position, 3. e3 is much better than 3.
c3 , because it keeps open the option of playing Nc3 in case Black plays Qb6
with a double-edged imbalanced position.} Nc6 {Black's alternative to
attacking the b2-pawn is to start piece development with pressure on d4. Black
can switch plans by playing ...Qb6 later, in which case we will most likely
transpose to the 3... Qb6 line.} 4. Nf3 {White continues developing his
kingside. It is better to wait with Nc3, as c2-c4 could be a strong idea
depending on Black's play.} Nf6 {Black develops his other knight as well.} 5.
dxc5 {Here White could play 5.c4 immediately, but I like to simplify here a
bit and take on c5 first.} e6 {The best move. Black secures the d5-square and
plans to take the pawn back on the next move.} 6. c4 {And now we reached a
Queen's Gambit Accepted structure with reversed colors and a tempo up for
White, where he used the tempo to bring the dark-squared bishop out to g5 in
front the pawn chain. It does look weird, but White's position is slightly
better with a clear plan and smooth play.} Bxc5 {Black develops his bishop and
recaptures the pawn.} 7. cxd5 {And now White dares Black into an IQP structure.
} exd5 8. Bb5 {White would like to play Nc3, Qc2, Rac1, and castle on the
short side. After that, the idea is to play Rfd1 and start pressing the
d5-pawn. Black, for the time, has two options. If he attacks the b5-bishop,
then White will just take the knight on c6 and play against the hanging c- and
d-pawns. And if not, White will wait for the best time to take on c6 anyway
and again attack the d5- and c6-pawns.} a6 {This move effectively loses a
tempo. Now White simply takes on c6 and starts playing against the pawns
according to his plan.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O {White castle before taking
action.} O-O {Black also moves his king away.} 11. Qc2 {The queen's x-ray
immediately attacks the c6-pawn behind the bishop.} Qe7 {Black must defend the
bishop. Otherwise, a crucial pawn would fall.} 12. Bxf6 {But now Black has
even more problems. Taking with the queen loses a piece and taking with the
pawn leaves his kingside pawn chain in ruins.} gxf6 13. Rc1 {White managed to
destroy the Black kingside and has a significant positional advantage already.
To add insult to injury, the c6-pawn is lost anyway. The rest is just a matter
of technique.} *

