1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Pseudo -
Trompowsky'! This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an
overview of the Pseudo - Trompowsky. With the Pseudo - Trompowsky, you will,
for sure, surprise your opponent and get him out of his preparation. It's
aggressive but simple to play and easy to learn. With this opening, you will
be creative right from the start. I did not analyze the absolute mainlines of
1. d4 that have been played oh so many times before, but the lines that I
found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c6 {This is the move that
Black plays in the Slav Defence after 2. c4, so you will see this move more
often than the original ...f6 here. It is much tougher than ...f6. Black would
like to consolidate the position and play solidly, like in the Slav. Also,
because White developed his dark-squared bishop quickly, Black would like to
take advantage of it and go for ...Qb6 with pressure on the b2-pawn.} 3. e3 {
White goes for his main setup after c6. Let us have a look at this position
and understand what is essential here. With 2... c6, Black keeps the reliable .
..Bf5 option open, and he could go for the adventurous ...Qb6 with immediate
pressure on the b2-pawn. Now the move order is essential. White has to go for
e3 to be prepared for ...Qb6 and to defend the d4-pawn. So, he only has to
think about how to deal with the ...Qxb2 threat.} Bf5 {This is the main
alternative to 3...Qb6 with more solid play from Black.} 4. Bd3 {White
exchanges the light-squared bishops to develop the pieces and get a small edge
quickly.} Bxd3 5. Qxd3 Qb6 {This move has a double purpose. The queen attacks
the b2-pawn and gets out of the pin, so Black can now play ...e6.} 6. Nc3 {
This is my recommendation again, jus as after the Black setup with ...Qb6 and .
..c5.} e6 {In many lines, only Black can go wrong and even lose in some of
them. It is much easier to play with White and Black has to be careful. Now
Black has to develop his kingside to castle short.} 7. Nge2 {White has many
different plans which are pretty good, but I like the plan with Nge2, long
castle and then playing for f3 and g4 or e4 with a more pleasant position to
play.} Nd7 {Black can develop his queenside with this move first, or the
kingside after 7...Be7.} 8. O-O-O {White castles long and gets ready for
action in the center.} Ngf6 9. f3 {The idea is to play e4 or g4 and stop the
Black knight from getting to e4.} Be7 10. h4 {White prepares a kingside attack
in case Black castles short.} O-O-O {Black can also castle long here.} 11. Kb1
{Just making the king safer.} Kb8 {Black does the same.} 12. e4 {White manages
to get a slight edge. He finished his development first and played in the
center. A clear plan is to play in the center with e4 and on the kingside with
g4.} *

