1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Pseudo -
Trompowsky'! This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an
overview of the Pseudo - Trompowsky. With the Pseudo - Trompowsky, you will,
for sure, surprise your opponent and get him out of his preparation. It's
aggressive but simple to play and easy to learn. With this opening, you will
be creative right from the start. I did not analyze the absolute mainlines of
1. d4 that have been played oh so many times before, but the lines that I
found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with many variations
that have never been played before. While this course might be useful even for
professional players, I mainly aim to deliver a repertoire to the strong
non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope you
enjoy this overview!} d5 {This is one of the two most frequent and most solid
and sound replies to 1. d4.} 2. Bg5 {This move reduces the number of
memorizable variations to the minimum. The arising positions are easy to play
and good for White with clear middlegame plans.} c6 {This is the move that
Black plays in the Slav Defence after 2. c4, so you will see this move more
often than the original f6 here. It is much tougher than f6. Black would like
to consolidate the position and play solidly, like in the Slav. Also, because
White developed his dark-squared bishop quickly, Black would like to take
advantage of it and go for Qb6 with pressure on the b2 pawn.} 3. e3 {White
goes for his main setup after c6. Let us have a look at this position and
understand what is essential here. With c6, Black keeps the reliable Bf5
option open, and he could go for the adventurous Qb6 with immediate pressure
on the b2 pawn. Now the move order is essential. White has to go for e3 to be
prepared for Qb6 and defend the d4 pawn. So, he only has to think about how to
deal with the Qxb2 threat.} Qb6 {This move is much more active than ...Bf5.
Black delays piece development for now and threaten to gain a material
advantage. These positions tend to become very sharp and, in my opinion, offer
White good chances to get an overwhelming initiative for the b2-pawn.} 4. Nf3 {
White sacrifices a pawn for the initiative. The moves will be quite forced for
some time. Black will lose time taking the b2-pawn and then lose some more
time to getting the queen back. White will use these tempi to obtain a big
advantage in development. In my opinion, this line is tricky to play for Black,
and the 3... Bf5 variations look much more solid. White will get a very
easy-to-play position with a clear plan and a lot of pressure.} Qxb2 {Black
has to take the pawn. Otherwise, the queen move was pointless. The only real
alternative is to play 4...Bf5 , with a transposition to the 3. ..Bf5
variation.} 5. Nbd2 {A developing move that also defends the rook.} Nf6 {Black
is behind in development, so he has to start bringing out his pieces on the
kingside and castle. Please note that Black cannot develop the light square
bishop right now because of Rb1.} 6. Bd3 {The best square for the bishop. It
will support the e4-break after castling.} e6 {Black has three options. He can
play 6...e6 immediately to develop the dark-squared bishop, 6...Nbd7 to defend
the f6-knight or the computer suggestion 6...Qa3. The main idea behind 6...e6
is to castle on the kingside as soon as possible.} 7. O-O {White wants to
castle immediately to be able to open the position in the center. He is way
ahead in development, so he has to open the game as fast as possible.} Be7 {
Now the dark-squared bishop is developed, and if White does not start
immediate operations, Black will castle on the next move.} 8. e4 {After
castling, White immediately has to start playing in the center to capitalize
on his development advantage.} dxe4 {Black cannot castle because he would lose
a piece, after 8...O-O 9.e5 , so he has to take on e4 first.} 9. Nxe4 {White
takes with the knight.} Nbd7 10. Nxf6+ {White trades a pair of knights and
will continue to play in the center with c4 and Rfe1.} Nxf6 11. c4 {The
position on the board is rather unclear, but White has great compensation for
the sacrificed pawn. It took a lot of time for Black to get the pawn, which
allowed White quick piece development, and Black will still have to spend some
time to get the queen on the b2-square back in the game. In my opinion, even
with the pawn minus White's advantage is obvious. Also, his plan is
straightforward: just go for moves like Re1, a4-a5 to gain some space on the
queenside, and Ne5 when possible.} *

